{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473323","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473323"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:06:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:06:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2346"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2346","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2346"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.72,0.16,0.03,0.07,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2346"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111638"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2346","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2346"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2346"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93706"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"148"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"2545"},{"type":"tags","id":"4807"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1288"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2670"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45441"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111638","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111638"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA two-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a six-day history of fever. His parent reports he developed a diffuse rash two days ago. His sister had a fever and sore throat one week ago. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 95/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 17/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 40.0\u00b0C. He has bilateral non-exudative conjunctivitis (Image), red cracked lips, a diffuse maculopapular rash, and erythema and oedema of his hands and feet. There is a 2 cm tender lymph node in the left cervical region.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intravenous immunoglobulin","Intravenous antibiotics","Oral penicillin","Paracetamol alone","Vitamin A supplementation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child presents with classic features of Kawasaki disease: fever \u22655 days plus four of the five diagnostic criteria, which can be recalled using the \u003Cstrong\u003ECOREL \u003C/strong\u003Emnemonic:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ebilateral non-exudative \u003Cstrong\u003Ec\u003C/strong\u003Eonjunctivitis,\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003Eo\u003C/strong\u003Eral changes (red cracked lips),\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Emaculopapular \u003Cstrong\u003Er\u003C/strong\u003Eash,\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003Ee\u003C/strong\u003Extremity changes (erythema and oedema), and\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ecervical \u003Cstrong\u003El\u003C/strong\u003Eymphadenopathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous immunoglobulin\u003C/strong\u003E is the definitive treatment for Kawasaki disease and must be administered within 10 days of symptom onset to prevent coronary artery complications. Aspirin is typically added despite the usual avoidance of aspirin in children (due to Reye syndrome risk) as the benefits outweigh the risks when treating Kawasaki disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for severe bacterial infections such as staphylococcal scalded skin syndrome, which can present with fever and rash. However, the combination of conjunctivitis, extremity changes and lymphadenopathy is more consistent with Kawasaki disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral penicillin\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for streptococcal pharyngitis. While there is a history of contact with a sibling with sore throat, this child\u0027s presentation is more extensive and characteristic of Kawasaki disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParacetamol alone\u003C/strong\u003E would be inadequate management given the risk of coronary artery complications without appropriate immunoglobulin therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVitamin A supplementation\u003C/strong\u003E is indicated for measles, which can present with fever, rash and conjunctivitis. However, measles typically includes cough, coryza and Koplik spots, which are absent here.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Kawasaki disease requires fever \u22655 days plus at least four of: conjunctivitis, oral changes, rash, extremity changes, and lymphadenopathy (recalled using the COREL mnemonic).","Intravenous immunoglobulin within 10 days prevents coronary artery complications in Kawasaki disease.","Aspirin is indicated in the treatment of Kawasaki disease despite the drug\u0027s general avoidance in children due to possible Reye syndrome."],"references":["Oates-Whitehead R, Baumer J, Haines L, Love S, Maconochie I, Gupta A et al. Intravenous immunoglobulin for the treatment of Kawasaki disease in children. Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews. 2003;.","Kawasaki disease. Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne Clinical Practice Guidelines. Updated January 2021. Available from: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Kawasaki_disease/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93706"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2346"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18677"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18677","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18677"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/29bef2ec-0b8b-478c-82b2-7e8aad34e67e.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/29bef2ec-0b8b-478c-82b2-7e8aad34e67e.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":580,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93706","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93706"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-17T16:17:07+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-17T16:18:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2346"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111638"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGrou